  "prompt": "To which class cin and cout belongs?",
  "response": "In C++, `cin` and `cout` belong to the `std::istream` and `std::ostream` classes respectively. More specifically:\n\n- `cin` is an object of the `std::istream` class, which is derived from the `std::ios` base class.\n- `cout` is an object of the `std::ostream` class, which is also derived from the `std::ios` base class.\n\nThese objects are part of the C++ Standard Library and are used for input and output operations. They are typically included in programs using the `<iostream>` header and are members of the `std` namespace.\n\nHere's a brief example to illustrate their usage:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n\nint main() {\n    int number;\n    \n    // Using cin for input\n    std::cout << \"Enter a number: \";\n    std::cin >> number;\n    \n    // Using cout for output\n    std::cout << \"You entered: \" << number << std::endl;\n    \n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `cin` is used to read input from the standard input stream, and `cout` is used to write output to the standard output stream.",
